AB  - Extended reality (XR) technologies as a pedagogical instrument have been transforming education by offering immersive learning experiences and enhanced instructional design. However, our understanding on how to leverage XR characteristics for optimal learning outcomes remains limited. This study investigates the mechanisms through which XR engagement, content quality, and interaction quality affect knowledge retention and skill development. Drawing on Experiential Learning Theory, we developed a comprehensive model of XR-enabled learning effectiveness. Using survey responses from 302 university students in China, we employed a multi-analytical approach, combining partial least squares structural equation modelling (PLS-SEM), necessary condition analysis (NCA), and fuzzy-set qualitative comparative analysis (fsQCA). Our findings reveal that, while XR engagement and interaction quality directly enhance knowledge retention, multiple configurations of XR characteristics can lead to desired learning outcomes, with knowledge retention as a crucial mediator. Additionally, we identify minimum threshold requirements of XR characteristics necessary for achieving learning effectiveness. This study uncovers both the causal pathways and configurational patterns through which XR influences learning outcomes. While XR's educational value emerges from its capacity to support pedagogical goals rather than technological features, our analysis implies how educational institutions shift from technology-driven implementations to pedagogy-centred integrations of XR affordances.
