AB  - PurposeThis study aims to examine the unique learning characteristics of digital natives - Generation Z and Alpha - and identifies challenges in adapting traditional teaching methods. It aims to bridge the gap between conventional pedagogies and digital natives' preferences by introducing a Structured Framework for Maximizing Engagement and Learning Efficiency.Design/methodology/approachThe study is literature-based, drawing on existing research to explore the learning characteristics of digital natives and the challenges educators face in adapting instructional strategies. Key databases like JSTOR and Google Scholar were used to review studies, particularly in developing countries, focusing on pedagogies that require minimal technological infrastructure.FindingsThe research proposes a framework for teachers to use the teaching period efficiently, aligning with digital natives' learning preferences. The framework integrates evidence-based strategies to enhance engagement and knowledge retention, fostering a more interactive and responsive learning environment.Research limitations/implicationsThe study relies heavily on existing literature, limiting real-world classroom insights. While adaptable, the framework's effectiveness may vary across cultural contexts and different countries.Practical implicationsThe framework offers strategies to improve teaching by making lessons more interactive and aligned with student preferences. It focuses on maximizing the use of class time through structured assessments and activities.Social implicationsThe framework could shift societal attitudes toward education, fostering a culture of lifelong learning. It also promotes cultural competence, creating an inclusive environment that values diversity.Originality/valueThe study provides educators with practical guidance to better engage digital natives, enhancing teaching quality and adapting instructional practices for diverse learning environments.
