AB  - Background: Retention of anatomy and physiology knowledge is essential for effective clinical practice, yet nursing students often struggle in these foundational courses. Aim: This study aimed to evaluate nursing students' retention of anatomy and physiology knowledge and determine whether learning styles and demographic factors influence this retention. Methods: A comparative cross-sectional study was conducted. A total of 209 undergraduate nursing students completed a 42-item multiple-choice test assessing anatomy and physiology knowledge and the VARK questionnaire to determine their preferred learning styles. Results: Knowledge retention declined significantly across cohorts, with the earliest cohort scoring the lowest. Kinesthetic learners showed higher knowledge retention than unimodal learners with other preferences (visual, aural, read/write). Male students demonstrated lower knowledge retention than female students. Conclusions: Incorporating anatomy and physiology courses throughout the entire degree plan may enhance long-term retention. Targeted support should be provided for unimodal learners other than kinesthetic, and specific interventions may benefit male students. Future research should explore the feasibility of shifting students' learning styles toward kinesthetic. (c) 2025 Organization for Associate Degree Nursing. Published by Elsevier Inc. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.
