AB  - Augmented reality (AR) has the potential to be a powerful educational tool, but AR may not be equally effective for all students in all learning environments. We developed an AR experience focused on coral reef ecology at the high school level and deployed it at a public aquarium. We measured efficacy through evaluations of knowledge retention, attitude, and user perception. Overall, our results indicate significant improvement in all students' knowledge, motivated attitudes, and positive perceptions of the technology's use inside and outside the classroom when learning about fundamental concepts within coral reef ecology. Learning outcomes were significantly higher for boys, though sample sizes were small. Given that previous work has shown gender biases in students' attitudes towards gamification, we hypothesize that certain aspects of the AR environment may have constrained girls' learning outcomes from AR. We conclude that while subject attitude affects learning achievement from other sources, the inclusion of gamified AR mechanics arouses the interest and motivation of all student types in a similar manner regardless of prior subject preferences. Our study overall highlights the potential for AR to be an effective and engaging learning tool in informal educational environments.
