KW  - engagement
AB  - BackgroundTraditional agricultural education in rural contexts demonstrates limitations in student engagement and knowledge retention. Studies suggest virtual reality (VR) implementation may enhance educational outcomes in resource-constrained environments.PurposeThis investigation examines how VR-mediated instruction affects academic performance, engagement, and attitudes among rural Agricultural Science undergraduates in Colombia.Design and methodThe study employed a quantitative experimental design with 250 undergraduate students across three Colombian universities. The experimental group (n = 125) utilized VR technology and AgriSphere software for soil nutrient management education, while the control group (n = 125) received traditional instruction over 14 weeks. Data collection included pre-test/post-test assessments, engagement measurements, and attitudinal surveys.ResultsStatistical analysis demonstrated significant improvement in academic performance for the experimental group compared to traditional instruction (experimental M = 85.0, SD = 8.5; control M = 80.0, SD = 9.0; t(248) = 2.90, p = 0.004, d = 0.63). The VR group exhibited higher engagement levels and more positive attitudes toward agricultural education. However, technical infrastructure limitations presented implementation challenges in some rural contexts.DiscussionThe findings indicate VR-mediated instruction effectiveness for agricultural education in rural settings. Given increasing emphasis on technology-enhanced learning, this study provides empirical evidence for educational technology integration in rural tertiary education. Future research should address technical infrastructure requirements and broader geographical applications.
