AB  - Due to an aging population, many manufacturing companies face the challenge of retaining essential knowledge and preventing the loss of valuable expert knowledge. Cognitive Support Technology (CST) is technology used to provide support for the cognitive or mental demands that work requires. This research uses the principles of CST from the employer's viewpoint. The question is: how can technological solutions such as Augmented Reality be used for knowledge retention by means of knowledge capture and instruction, and which manufacturing processes are most suitable for this? Six industrial companies were involved in a two-pronged approach for data collection, involving a canvas session to identify general needs and a cognitive task analysis to further elaborate on the appropriate processes. All companies found at least some relevant process for implementation of AR for cognitive support, especially when it comes to AR instruction; for knowledge capture, more traditional methods involving paper or video are often preferred. We found various relevant cognitive challenges, including mental rotation for 3D images, as well as practical challenges for implementation, such as protective equipment that might interfere with AR solutions. One of the companies also took part in a pilot in order to test AR solutions for knowledge capture and instruction. It was found that employees appreciate the cognitive support, but have some reservations about practical issues such as the heaviness of the AR systems. Further research will focus on developing these AR solutions for the identified processes, as well as the implementation and evaluation of these solutions.
